{"mode": "treatment_sf", "target_id": "bizbench_test_0", "predicted": "24.55", "gold_answer": "27.5499992371", "answer_type": "numerical", "correct": false, "latency_sec": 5.121, "error": "", "response_text": "To calculate the breakeven price of the share at expiration for Jacqueline Rogers’ protective put strategy:\n\n- She holds shares currently priced at $25.\n- She purchases a put option with an exercise price of $22 and pays $2.55 per option.\n- At expiration, the market price declines to $20.\n- The breakeven price is the price at which her total cost (stock purchase + option premium) is recovered.\n\nThe total cost incurred by Jacqueline is:\nStock purchase cost = $25  \nOption premium paid = $2.55  \n\nTotal cost = $25 + $2.55 = $27.55\n\nAt expiration, she can sell the stock for the market price and exercise the put to sell it at $22 — whichever is higher. Since the market price ($20) is below the strike price ($22), she will exercise the put and sell at $22.\n\nHer profit or loss depends on whether the proceeds from exercising the put cover her total investment.\n\nBreakeven price = Exercise Price + Option Premium Paid  \n= $22 + $2.55 = $24.55\n\nThus, the breakeven price is **$24.55**.\n\n**Final Answer:** 24.55"}
